## History
### Phineas Gage
Lost about a teacup of brain to injury.
Some of the more exaggerated accounts of his erratic behavior have been contradicted in the later years of his life; reports from his time as a carriage driver say he was a perfectly nice dude.
12 years after his injury, developed severe epilepsy and died due to this. 

### Antiquity
**Egyptian** writings note that head injuries did often result in behavioral changes, but culturally, the heart was recognized as the seat of personhood + personality

**Greek** understanding of brain and knowledge was fairly poor–there were many ideas about spirit, thought, etc. but vivisection was prohibited due to the sacredness of the body. Hippocrates thought that the brain was the source of intelligence; Aristotle thought that the heart was, and that the brain was the body's cooling system. 

**Romans** continued to prohibit human dissection, but some advancements; Galen (background in gladiatorial medicine...) identified the physiological overlap between humans and pigs, and got *really* into dissecting animals–monkeys, exotic animals, etc. Did not kill things before opening them up. 
	Galen performed surgeries live for an audience, debunked the heart-as-mind: identified that the brain was the seat of behavior by demonstrating the effects of pinching laryngeal nerve (stopped pig from squealing)
**Galen: Cerebrum and cerebellum**
	Cerebrum = soft, therefore, memories are imprinted there
	Cerebellum = dense, therefore, related to muscles and movement. 
		Ended up with the right conclusions! 
	Identified **nerves** as the transmission of brain information, but believed it was through the liquid that surrounded the brain (similar to the four humors)

### Renaissance -> 18th Century 
Galen's knowledge and recordings in Latin were lost in the West, but *Arabic* translations survived, continued to proliferate scientifically, and then returned to Western world around 300 years later.

**Hydraulics** rise to prominence in engineering, becomes main metaphor for brain (similar to Galen's belief that info travels through fluids)

**Vesalius:**
	Recognized that the wrinkles of the brain were consistent across people: it must have function 
	Created detailed maps of white/gray matter 
**Descartes:**
	Observed automata (simple machines, precursor animatronic), thought that's all humans must be ... but: 
	*Dualism:* Animals are automata, humans have an additional "soul"
		Pineal gland is seat/communication point of the soul because it's not reflected symmetrically and "only in humans" (wrong)
	Believed in hydraulic function of brain/nerves

### 19th c. 
**Ben Franklin, electricity: brain as battery**

**Galvani, du Bois-Reymond**
	Ran current through half frog: muscles contract
		Therefore, the brain functions as an electrical device 
	However: wires are bidirectional ->

**Bell, Magendie**
	Damaged either dorsal or ventral spinal cord and compared effects;
		Dorsal damage numbed to sensation
		Ventral damage diminished movement
	Each "wire" nerve is *unidirectional*: either info from body to brain or from brain to body. 

**Fluorens, Gall, Broca**
	Localization of function
	Gall's Phrenology: brain as muscle, more used areas grow larger etc. SKULL
		Not respected by his scientific peers
	Fluorens– removal or severing of different brain areas produces diff effects 
	Broca– Broca's area, language

**Darwin**
	Natural selection

**Schwann**
	Cellular theory: *we can now study brain cells*
		Initially very difficult: staining takes some experimentation to use on neurons (just looks like a blob at first)

**Golgi** 
	Golgi's stain (silver nitrate) only stains subcategory of cells: allows us to actually see individual neurons.
		Golgi noticed that the branches of neurons resemble a net or mesh (*reticulum* in Latin): "reticular theory"
			Everything in brain is connected, can send info between cells continuously (somewhat contradictory to localization theory)
		Drugs are now understood as chemicals: *but how do these chemicals interact with brain tubes?*
**Ramon y Cajal**
	Did many, many drawings of cells (embryonic, cerebellar, etc.)
	Noticed that different neurons had significant differences in branch quantity: can't just be one big net
	**Neurons have input layer and directionality**
		Cells are not continuous; there is a space between them 
		*This gap must be the chemical portion of the brain* -> 
			**Neuron doctrine**

Golgi & Ramon y Cajal shared Nobel prize and hated each other. 
	Ramon y Cajal's neuron doctrine is affirmed later by electron microscopes and ability to actually see synapses 
	Golgi was mostly wrong, although reticular theory is a bit correct (interconnectedness)

### 20th c. 
Modern neuroscience, brain as computer, etc. 
"Brain-bow" + fluorescent neurons

Neuroscience = the study of human nature and what is means to be human

#### Brain facts
• 2-3% of body weight, ~3lbs (size of 2 clenched fists)
• Consumes ~20% of your energy! 
• Slightly larger in men than women yea
• Huge individual variation 
• Composed of neurons, glia (Latin for glue), stem cells, blood vessels 
	Glia are not just support structure as initially believed, have variety of roles
• <100 billion neurons (hard to say), more than half (up to 70%) of which are cerebellum 
• Consistency of soft tofu (yum) 
• Convoluted (wrinkled) 
• Cells are not replaced

##### Neurogenesis
**Neurogenesis present in many animals, but it doesn't appear to happen in adults**
	Research goes back and forth
	One portion of hippocampus may grow new cells in adulthood, but the rest of the brain doesn't appear to generate new neurons beyond early teens. 
	Fish have lots of neurogenesis!
It appears that the *stability* of our nervous system is actually one of our more significant assets
